\ id kofbgukzdvgkwkxs
* "lambda" is synonym of 'function literal'
* the syntax
	* is usually similar to "<intro> <input> <sep> <output>", where
		* <intro> is usually one of
			* "fun"
				* as a shorter version of "function"
			* "lambda"
			* "λ"
				* the greek character pronounced as "lambda"
				* it was the first notation and this is where the the name comes from
			* ""
				* nothing
			* "\"
				* for example in haskell
				* looks visually similar to "λ"
		* <input> is a name, here introduced, for the input of the function
		* <sep>
			* separates the [name of the] input from the rest of the function definition
			*  is usually one of
				* "->"
					* this is most common in practical programming languages
				* "."
					* this is most common in mathematical text, especially lambda calculus
				* ":"
					* rare
		* <output>
			* is an expression whose value to be mapped by the function to the input
	* example
		* fun x -> x + 1
